ent cultural manifestations. Barczewski offers a rare scholarly analysis of the history of country houses that goes beyond an architectural or biographical study, and recognises their importance as the physical embodiments of imperial wealth and reflectors of imperial cultural influences. In so doing, she restores them to their true place of centrality in British culture over the last three centuries, and provides fresh insights into the role of the Empire in the British metropolis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aBritish Empire.  aEast India Company.  abell-pull system.  acollecting.  acommodities.  aconquest.  acosmopolitanism.  acountry houses.  acultural impact.  afree traders.  aimperial cultural influences.  aimperial wealth.  alanded estates.  alanded magnates.  anabobs.  anational imperial engagement.  aplanters.1 aBarczewski, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packagez978311128357940uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611753340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526117533423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526117533/original  a978-3-11-128357-9  Manchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packageb2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles